nsulin-induced gene 1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9983519315719604, "span": {"begin": 396, "end": 418}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3638"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "INSIG1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9984954595565796, "span": {"begin": 420, "end": 426}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3638"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "INSIG1 protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9903594851493835, "span": {"begin": 487, "end": 501}}], "text": "Pregnane X receptor (PXR) is a nuclear receptor that, once activated, binds to Retinoid X receptor (RXR), resulting in regulation of target genes, with an important role in maintenance of lipid homeostasis by affecting rates of glucose synthesis, cholesterol synthesis, lipid synthesis, and lipid uptake (Lv et al. 2022). &nbsp;Increased Pregnane X Receptor (PXR) activation results in decreased insulin-induced gene 1 (INSIG1) protein activity, suggested through destabilization of the INSIG1 protein (Karpale et al. 2021; Itkonen et al. 2023), resulting in increased lipid synthesis.&nbsp; &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:14:08 +0000 2026"}